coming out
of the wood.

42:10.495 --> 42:16.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, sometimes, you see them
with their kids
on their back, and that is
really a problem.

42:16.234 --> 42:20.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Household air
pollution
from the burning of biomass
fuel, like wood

42:20.538 --> 42:25.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and charcoal, is known to cause
respiratory
diseases, such as pneumonia, as
well as chronic

42:25.743 --> 42:27.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pulmonary and cardiovascular
diseases.

42:27.712 --> 42:29.380 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

42:29.414 --> 42:32.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KWAKU POKU ASANTE: I'm really
committed to
this, because millions of people
die from

42:32.784 --> 42:35.520 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
these illnesses, and we have to
do something
about it.

42:35.553 --> 42:37.355 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We have to stop it.

42:37.388 --> 42:42.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Dr. Abena
Yawson is a public
health physician with the
Kintampo Health

42:42.493 --> 42:43.461 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Research Center.

42:43.494 --> 42:45.396 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

42:45.430 --> 42:47.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABENA YAWSON, Kintampo Health
Research Center:
This is the pediatric ward for
Kintampo Municipal

42:47.932 --> 42:48.900 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Hospital.

42:48.933 --> 42:51.068 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You can see it's very busy.

42:51.102 --> 42:55.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This baby was admitted because
of fever and
cough.

42:55.706 --> 43:01.579 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The mother noted she was
breathing with difficulty,
and we actually have diagnosed
the child as

43:01.612 --> 43:03.247 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
having bronchial pneumonia.

43:03.281 --> 43:07.251 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's using charcoal in a
traditional cookstove
to cook.

43:07.285 --> 43:13.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there are times that, when
she's cooking,
and she's fanning the fire, she
coughs, because

43:13.925 --> 43:15.960 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
she gets to inhale smoke.

43:15.993 --> 43:20.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Pregnant women
and their
children face the most risk from
these diseases,

43:21.032 --> 43:25.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the objective of this study
in Kintampo
is to look at the impact of
household air

43:25.203 --> 43:31.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pollution on low birth weight
and pneumonia
among about 1,400 pregnant women
and their

43:31.709 --> 43:35.346 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
children in 35 communities in
the study area.

43:35.379 --> 43:40.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Professor Darby Jack at Columbia
University
is a partner with the Ghanaians
on the project,

43:40.218 --> 43:42.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
supported by the U.S. National
Institutes
of Health.

43:42.220 --> 43:46.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DARBY JACK, Columbia University:
We recruit
women during pregnancy, and we
give them a

43:46.224 --> 43:51.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
clean-burning cookstove, either
LPG, which
is the propane or butane, the
same thing you

43:51.329 --> 43:56.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
probably cook with in your
backyard grill,
or a stove called the BioLite,
which is an

43:56.567 --> 44:01.305 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
efficient biomass burning stove,
and can reduce
emissions by about half.

44:01.339 --> 44:06.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The study
measures exposure
to carbon monoxide from the
cookstoves and

44:06.110 --> 44:11.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to small particles in the smoke,
particulates
that can penetrate deep into
lungs and enter

44:11.082 --> 44:12.884 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the bloodstream.

44:12.917 --> 44:16.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DARBY JACK: So, we deploy
personal monitors
that mothers can wear and the
children can

44:16.787 --> 44:19.023 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
wear for 72 hours at a time.

44:19.056 --> 44:23.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: At regular
intervals, exposure
monitors are collected and their
data is downloaded.

44:23.694 --> 44:26.564 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DARBY JACK: We set out to test
two hypotheses.

44:26.597 --> 44:31.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The first is that reducing
exposure to household
air pollution will increase
birth weight.

44:31.035 --> 44:36.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then the second hypothesis
is that reduced
exposure will reduce the rate of
pneumonia

44:36.707 --> 44:38.509 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in the first year of life.

44:38.543 --> 44:42.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The core questions here are, how
clean is
clean enough?

44:42.613 --> 44:44.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then, number two, what
technologies will
bring us there?

44:44.949 --> 44:46.684 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

44:46.717 --> 44:50.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KWAKU POKU ASANTE: We are not in
a position
to recommend any of the stoves
that we have

44:50.388 --> 44:51.355 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
tested.

44:51.389 --> 44:53.658 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That will be left with the
policy-makers.

44:53.691 --> 44:55.459 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Ours is to generate the
evidence.

44:55.493 --> 44:59.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The evidence
is still incomplete,
but results so far are
encouraging.

44:59.530 --> 45:01.432 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

45:01.465 --> 45:05.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABENA YAWSON: I'm sure all the
household actually
might have gotten high exposure
to smoke because

45:05.570 --> 45:10.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of how close it is also to the
building that
they live in.

45:10.274 --> 45:17.381 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this is what the woman was
using until
the BioLite was given to her.

45:17.415 --> 45:24.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She actually enjoys cooking with
the BioLite
because she doesn't get sore
eyes after cooking,

45:24.121 --> 45:29.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the coughs that used to be
very frequent
with the traditional cookstove
are also not

45:29.961 --> 45:30.928 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
there.

45:30.962 --> 45:35.032 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, the baby hasn't been ill
since birth.

45:35.066 --> 45:38.569 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He has very good reflexes.

45:38.603 --> 45:39.971 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He's pink.

45:40.004 --> 45:42.473 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He's not pale.

45:42.506 --> 45:48.346 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, he's looking generally very
beautiful
and healthy.

45:48.379 --> 45:49.347 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Bye-bye.

45:49.380 --> 45:51.215 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

45:51.248 --> 45:55.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KWAKU POKU ASANTE: I would like
to see, in
the next decade, to see the
burden of pneumonia

45:55.786 --> 45:59.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
come down and also to see people
use improved
cookstoves.

45:59.991 --> 46:05.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would like to see a commitment
from other
partners, if we show the
evidence that the

46:05.997 --> 46:10.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
use of improved cookstoves
reduces the burden
of many diseases.

46:10.568 --> 46:15.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And there's
another benefit
to be expected from improved
cookstoves.

46:15.373 --> 46:19.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Women and young girls spend
hours every day
gathering wood for fuel.

46:19.477 --> 46:23.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Released from that burden, they
could spend
more time going to school or
caring for their

46:23.547 --> 46:24.515 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
children.

46:24.548 --> 46:28.719 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Hari
Sreenivasan.

46:28.753 --> 46:41.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Now: the toll of
cervical cancer
and recent findings that suggest
its death

46:41.766 --> 46:43.501 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
rate is higher than we thought.

46:43.534 --> 46:47.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's the focus of our weekly
segment the
Leading Edge.

46:47.271 --> 46:52.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Estimates had shown more than
4,000 women
in the U.S. die from cervical
cancer each

46:52.543 --> 46:57.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
year, and that the death rate
dropped dramatically
over past decades.

46:57.314 --> 47:02.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But an analysis published in the
journal "Cancer"
found the mortality rate is
higher than previously

47:02.553 --> 47:06.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
thought, and it is significantly
higher among
African-American women.

47:06.991 --> 47:11.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The findings were particularly
concerning
because cervical cancer can
often be prevented

47:11.729 --> 47:16.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
through better screening, and
the HPV vaccine
can prevent some cases.

47:16.701 --> 47:21.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dr. Jennifer Caudle is a family
physician
and an assistant professor at
Rowan University.

47:21.772 --> 47:26.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She has been writing about these
findings
and the implications for her
clinical practice,

47:26.977 --> 47:28.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and she joins us now to tell us
a little bit
more.

47:29.013 --> 47:30.481 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Dr. Caudle, good to have you
with us.

47:30.514 --> 47:31.582 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

47:31.615 --> 47:32.750 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JENNIFER CAUDLE, Rowan
University: Thanks
so much.

47:32.783 --> 47:34.051 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Tell us what's
new about this
study.

47:34.085 --> 47:35.352 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

47:35.386 --> 47:37.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENNIFER CAUDLE: Well, I think
it's actually
quite profound.

47:37.288 --> 47:42.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As a family physician myself, as
a woman myself,
I thought that the results of
the study were

47:42.159 --> 47:43.961 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
actually quite staggering.

47:43.994 --> 47:48.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Basically, researchers found
that we'd been
underestimating the levels of
cervical cancer

47:48.532 --> 47:50.501 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
mortality.

47:50.534 --> 47:54.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And not only that, but we have
also been underestimating
the amount of racial disparities
that exist

47:54.972 --> 47:56.340 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in cervical cancer mortality.

47:56.373 --> 48:00.811 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, basically, the problem is
bigger and worse
than we thought.

48:00.845 --> 48:02.646 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think that it's actually
quite significant.

48:02.680 --> 48:06.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, so, let's,
first of all,
talk about the underestimation
in general.

48:06.250 --> 48:07.752 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How could something like that
happen?

48:07.785 --> 48:10.888 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This was a study of studies,
taking a second
look at numbers, right?

48:10.921 --> 48:11.889 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

48:11.922 --> 48:13.190 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JENNIFER CAUDLE: That's right.

48:13.224 --> 48:13.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: And what did they
find that
others overlooked?

48:13.924 --> 48:14.892 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

48:14.925 --> 48:16.594 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JENNIFER CAUDLE: Right.

48:16.627 --> 48:17.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, that's a great question,
because the
key here -- and I always say the
devil is

48:17.328 --> 48:19.230 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the details.

48:19.263 --> 48:22.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The key with this particular
study is, they
took into account whether a
woman had a hysterectomy

48:22.833 --> 48:24.635 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
or not.

48:24.668 --> 48:27.471 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Now, when we talk about
hysterectomy, a complete
hysterectomy often is when a
woman has her

48:27.505 --> 48:29.306 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
cervix removed.

48:29.340 --> 48:32.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, if you can imagine, if a
woman doesn't
have a cervix, her chance of
getting cervical

48:32.243 --> 48:34.311 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
cancer is slim to none.

48:34.345 --> 48:39.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That, along with the fact that
black women
tend to have a higher prevalence
of hysterectomies,

48:39.316 --> 48:43.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you can see how both of those
factors, when
they're actually taken into
consideration,

48:43.854 --> 48:45.589 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can cause the results that we
saw.

48:45.623 --> 48:49.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, basically, when researchers
looked at
whether a woman had a
hysterectomy or not,

48:49.794 --> 48:54.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we found that our prior results
actually had
been underestimated, and more
women had cervical

48:54.832 --> 48:58.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cancer mortality rates, higher
rates, and
more racial disparities that
than we thought.

48:58.636 --> 49:02.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So, you really
don't have to
be a scientist to realize that,
if you remove

49:02.807 --> 49:05.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the group of people who don't
have a cervix
at all, you are going to have a
different

49:06.010 --> 49:07.778 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
set of numbers.

49:07.812 --> 49:11.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But let's -- help us understand
a little bit
more about why African-American
women might

49:11.916 --> 49:13.651 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
disproportionately be affected.

49:13.684 --> 49:14.652 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

49:14.685 --> 49:15.820 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JENNIFER CAUDLE: Right.

49:15.853 --> 49:17.621 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I'm really glad that we're
talking about
this.

49:17.655 --> 49:21.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I wrote my op-ed piece, you
know, I was
speaking as a family physician,
but also as

49:21.659 --> 49:22.726 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a black woman.

49:22.760 --> 49:25.963 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And racial disparities in health
care, it's
not new.

49:25.996 --> 49:30.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Unfortunately, we see racial
disparities in
health care in cervical cancer
here, but also

49:30.568 --> 49:32.636 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in many other cancers and other
conditions.

49:32.670 --> 49:36.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But one of the things that we're
looking at
is why exactly these racial
disparities exist.

49:36.740 --> 49:41.111 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And, yes, there are many
organizations that
have been working on this sort
of topic globally.

49:41.145 --> 49:42.980 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And there's not one answer.

49:43.013 --> 49:47.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we do think there might be
some reasons
why black women have higher
rates of cervical

49:47.751 --> 49:53.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cancer mortality, some of those
being access
to care, the ability to get
screened early,

49:53.157 --> 49:58.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to get screened period, the type
of cancer
that black women get vs. white
women, and

49:58.162 --> 49:59.930 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the types of treatments that are
offered.

49:59.964 --> 50:05.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, those are some of the things
that have
been posed as possibilities as
to why we see

50:05.469 --> 50:06.437 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the discrepancy.

50:06.470 --> 50:09.506 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the bottom line is, it's
unfortunate.

50:09.540 --> 50:11.342 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's something we have to
keep talking
about.

50:11.375 --> 50:14.645 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: This is a
particularly poignant
one for those of us here at the
"NewsHour."

50:14.678 --> 50:19.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Of course, in November, we lost
Gwen Ifill
to gynecological cancer, a
different kind

50:19.216 --> 50:21.018 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of gynecological cancer.

50:21.051 --> 50:25.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the case of cervical cancer,
I know it's
very difficult for families who
are affected,

50:25.856 --> 50:29.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because, with screening, and in
some cases
a vaccine, it can be prevented.

50:29.960 --> 50:30.928 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

50:30.961 --> 50:32.863 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JENNIFER CAUDLE: That's right.

50:32.897 --> 50:34.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's, I think, one of the
most important
points here, is, as we're
looking at the global

50:34.865 --> 50:38.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issue of why are there racial
disparities,
why are there higher mortality
rates than

50:38.702 --> 50:41.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we thought, we also need to look
at what we
do have.

50:41.272 --> 50:42.473 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And you're right.

50:42.506 --> 50:44.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have a screening tool to
screen for cervical
cancer.

50:44.608 --> 50:47.311 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's the Pap smear, along with
the HPV Testing.

50:47.344 --> 50:51.148 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We also have the HPV, or human
papilloma virus,
vaccine.

50:51.181 --> 50:54.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That was made available in 2006,
and it is
indicated for young women.

50:54.585 --> 50:59.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It doesn't protect against all
strains of
HPV that can cause cervical
cancer, but it

50:59.456 --> 51:01.125 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
does protect against many of
them.

51:01.158 --> 51:04.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the hope is that, in further
years, we're
going to see the benefit of that
vaccine.

